{
  "texts": [
    "The two conditions on b ij allow to ensure its integrability on the sphere and the positivity of such integral.In particular, the upper bound on b ij is classical [18,21,28,36,42] and implies Grad's cutoff assumption.",
    "Finally, the last assumption on b ii in (EL4) is satisfied by all relevant physical models and is needed to recover a spectral gap for the linearized operator associated with Q EL [21,42].Remark 1.",
    "We point out that one could replace the rather restrictive assumption (EL3) on the kinetic part Φ ij (|v -v * |) with the following more general condition:(EL3') There exist three constantsC ij, C ij > 0 and γ ij = γ ji ∈ [0, 1] such that C ij |v -v * | γ ij ≤ Φ ij (|v -v * |) ≤ C ij 1 + |v -v * |, ∀v, v * ∈ R 3.However, in this case one must also enforce (see [28, Section 1.3, condition (A6)]) that for any 1 ≤ i ≤ 4 the elastic multi-species collision frequency(8) ν EL i (v) = 4 j=1 R 3 ×S 2 B ij (|v -v * |, cos θ)µ j (v *)dv * dσ, v ∈ R 3.is controlled by the corresponding monospecies componentν EL ii (v) = R 3 ×S 2 B ii (|v -v * |, cos θ)µ i (v *)dv * dσ, v ∈ R 3,This amounts to impose the additional condition (EL5) There exists a constant β EL > 0 such that, for any 1 ≤ i ≤ 4, it holdsν EL i (v) ≤ β EL ν EL ii (v), ∀v ∈ R 3.Hypothesis (EL3') would allow to consider more general collision kernels of power law-type that possess different species-dependent exponents [1,18] of the formΦ ij (|v -v * |) = C ij |v -v * | γ ij, with γ ij ∈ [0, 1].We emphasize that the lower bound in (EL3') is a minimal requirement needed to recover quantitative estimates on the spectral gap of the inert Boltzmann operator [28].",
    "The same consideration holds for the upper bound, which imposes that the kinetic part is of restricted growth for both small and large values of |v -v * |.",
    "We stress however that (EL3') alone is not enough to obtain explicit controls on the spectral gap of the multi-species Boltzmann operator [28] and must be combined with assumption (EL5) to guarantee the validity of Theorem 1."
  ]
}